ce:section.ce:para:
Arsenic [As (III),
AsO 2 −
] contamination in drinking water is a burning problem in developing countries (Fendorf et al., 2010). Among the various forms, As (III) is considered as the most harmful contaminants (Jena and Raj, 2008). A number of diseases such as skin damage, problems with circulatory system and high risk lung or bladder cancer (Hughes et al., 2011; Borgono et al., 1977) are related with the continuous intake of As (III) in drinking water, above the World Health Organization (WHO) approved level of 10ppb (133nM, 10μg/L) (Ezeh and Harrop, 2012). Several standard techniques have been reported in literature for the ultrasensitive detection of As (III) (Table S1). To date, many methods (Francesconi and Kuehnelt, 2004) have been established to determine As (III) concentration, including hydride generation atomic fluorescence spectrometry (HG-AFS) (Yin et al., 2002), atomic absorption spectroscopy (AAS) (Aggett and Aspell, 1976), inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry (ICPMS) (Yan et al., 1998) and anodic stripping voltammetry (SWASV-CV) (Dai et al., 2004). Although, among the methods, SWASV-CV and ICPMS showed their application for As (III) sensing with a DL up to 10 and 28pM respectively, (Gao et al., 2013; Sengupta and Dasgupta, 2009), however these techniques require costly instrumental facilities, time-consuming complex sample preparation process and moreover the requirement of trained personnel. As a result they are not very much useful for on-site detection. To over come the above limitations colorimetric sensors have been found to be effective for As (III) detection (Sirawatcharin et al., 2014). DNA or polymer conjugated gold nanoparticles have been demonstrated for the efficient As (III) detection but again they are cost effective and rely on accurate control of the detection conditions, such as temperature which limits their practical application (Wu et al., 2012; Kalluri et al., 2009).

Finally, the as synthesized CNDs have been used as photo switchable probe for super resolution imaging on bacterial nucleoid segregation (Lamothe et al., 2008; Spahn et al., 2014). The super resolution imaging has a great potential, especially for visualizing the dynamical event in cytoskeleton and other biological process down to nanometer resolution under live cell condition. In presence of an electron acceptor (MV), the CNDs create a stable dark state (OFF state), which facilitates the Photoswitching (
                        Figs. 6a and S15
                        ) (Khan et al., 2015a,b). An electron donor (AA) showed the reverse effect. Although the normal image in Fig. 6b (left panel) showed a blurred image, the super resolution image showed distinct two bright points, most probably the centroid of the two segregated nucleoid (Fig. 6b, right panel). The relative distance between the structures increased in elongated cells probably indicating spatially symmetric chromosome segregation throughout the cell division cycle.
